RCA Methodology
\series default
:
 This policy shall not prescribe a specific root cause analysis methodology.
 The Investigator shall select and apply the analytical approach best suited to the failure condition under investigation.
 The obligation is that root cause analysis is conducted rigorously,
 documented completely,
 and produces a finding that is specific enough to support a permanent remediation proposal.
 The methodology used shall be noted in the Problem record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Separation of Investigative and Remediation Authority
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Problem management process is divided into two distinct phases with different authority structures:
 Execution and Authorization.
 This separation ensures that investigative capability is distributed across all staff tiers while permanent system changes remain subject to appropriate oversight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Execution —
 The Investigation
\series default
:
 The assigned Investigator,
 at any staff tier,
 shall be fully authorized to conduct all investigative activities described in Section 6.3 without restriction or additional approval.
 The Investigator shall not require supervisory sign-off to analyze logs,
 review configurations,
 trace network paths,
 or pursue any other analytical activity in furtherance of root cause identification.
 Investigation is the Investigator's domain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Authorization —
 The Fix
\series default
:
 The Investigator shall not implement any permanent system change,
 configuration modification,
 patch deployment,
 architectural adjustment,
 or other remediation action independently.
 Once the Investigator has identified root cause and developed a remediation proposal,
 the following authorization process applies before any remediation action is taken:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
The Investigator shall document the proposed remediation in full in the Problem record,
 including:
 the root cause finding,
 the proposed corrective action,
 the systems affected,
 the implementation plan,
 and any risks or dependencies associated with the remediation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
The Investigator shall notify the Assistant IT Director that a remediation proposal is ready for review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall review the proposal and shall provide a documented recommendation to the IT Director within three (3) business days of notification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
The IT Director shall review the proposal and the Assistant IT Director's recommendation and shall issue a written authorization or denial within five (5) business days of the Assistant IT Director's recommendation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
Remediation shall not commence until the IT Director's written authorization is documented in the Problem record.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
If the IT Director denies the proposed remediation,
 the denial shall be documented with rationale in the Problem record.
 The Investigator may develop an alternative remediation proposal,
 which shall follow the same authorization process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Problem record shall not be closed without IT Director sign-off,
 regardless of whether a remediation has been implemented.
 A Problem record that reaches closure without a viable permanent remediation shall be closed as a Known Error in accordance with Section 6.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Known Error Management and Knowledge Base Publication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A Known Error is a Problem for which root cause has been identified but for which a permanent remediation has not yet been implemented,
 whether because the remediation is pending authorization,
 pending resources,
 pending a vendor fix,
 or has been determined not to be cost-effective relative to an available workaround.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Known Error Declaration
\series default
:
 When the Investigator identifies root cause and determines that a permanent remediation will not be immediately implemented —
 for any reason —
 the Investigator shall notify the Assistant IT Director and shall declare a Known Error condition in the Problem record.
 The Known Error declaration shall include:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The identified root cause.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The reason a permanent remediation is not immediately forthcoming.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
A documented workaround sufficient to restore or maintain service for affected users in the interim.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Knowledge Base Publication
\series default
:
 Upon Known Error declaration,
 the Assistant IT Director shall ensure that the documented workaround is published to the Knowledge Base maintained under Policy 3.13 within two (2) business days of the declaration.
 The published entry shall include the symptoms that identify the Known Error condition,
 the workaround procedure,
 and the Problem record number for traceability.
 Publication to the Knowledge Base shall not be deferred pending Problem closure.
\end_layout

